This is not really a `nil` value like a standard attribute. Contact has_one Address so there needs to be a record in the database or the instance has to have been joined to an unpersisted object (below) if you are going to use `as_json`.

I have two ideas for how to approach this, but first I&#39;m a bit surprised at this part of your data:

    contact: {
        id: 1,
        full_name: &quot;contact name goes here&quot;,
        address: {
              title: &#39;this is the address&#39;
           }
        }
    }

I&#39;m not sure if it&#39;s at the root of your problem, but are you sure you didn&#39;t hand code this? I would expect an address.id to be present:

    contact: {
        id: 1,
        full_name: &quot;contact name goes here&quot;,
        address: {
             id: 1,
             title: &#39;this is the address&#39;
           }
        }
    }

My **first suggestion** would be something like

    lease.contact.address = Address.new unless lease.contact.address

This will probably get what you want, but I haven&#39;t tested it.

My **second suggestion** would be to consider using a formal serializer to get another layer of logic and processing between your active model records and your JSON. You can define &quot;attributes&quot; that are computed in methods.

I have had good results with [fast_jsonapi][1] 


  [1]: https://github.com/Netflix/fast_jsonapi

If you must use a loop, you can use:

    def swap(num):
        res = &quot;&quot;
        for ind, char in enumerate(str(num)):
            if ind == 0:
                last = char
            elif ind &lt; len(str(num))-1:
                res += char
            else:
                res = char + res + last
        return int(res)

however, a much better way is to use slicing:

    def swap(num):
        str_num = str(num)
        str_swapped = str_num[-1] + str_num[1:-1] + str_num[0]
        return int(str_swapped)

Here is another way to achieve your goal.

    def swap(numbers):
        numbersList = []
        for number in str(numbers):
            numbersList.append(number)
        numbersList[0], numbersList[-1] = numbersList[-1], numbersList[0]
        return int(&#39;&#39;.join(numbersList))

